  "prompt": "How many 3-digit numbers can be formed using only 2, 3, 4, 7 and 8 with no repeats?",
  "response": "To determine how many 3-digit numbers can be formed using the digits 2, 3, 4, 7, and 8 with no repeats, we can follow a systematic approach:\n\n1. **Identify the digits available**: The digits we can use are 2, 3, 4, 7, and 8, making a total of 5 different digits.\n\n2. **Select the digits for the 3-digit number**: Since we want to create a 3-digit number and no digits can be reused within that number (i.e., no repetitions), we will select 3 digits from the available 5.\n\n3. **Arrangement of selected digits**: After selecting any 3 digits, they can be arranged in different ways to form a number. The number of arrangements of 3 digits is calculated using the factorial notation \\(3!\\).\n\nNow, we can calculate the total number of 3-digit numbers as follows:\n\n- **Choose 3 digits out of 5**: The number of ways to select 3 digits from the 5 available digits can be computed using combinations:\n\n\\[\n\\binom{5}{3} = \\frac{5!}{3!(5-3)!} = \\frac{5 \\times 4}{2 \\times 1} = 10\n\\]\n\n- **Arrange the selected digits**: For each selection of 3 digits, the number of ways to arrange these 3 digits is given by \\(3!\\):\n\n\\[\n3! = 6\n\\]\n\n- **Calculate the total number of 3-digit numbers**: The total number of different 3-digit numbers that can be formed is the product of the number of ways to choose the digits and the number of ways to arrange those digits:\n\n\\[\n\\text{Total numbers} = \\text{Ways to choose 3 digits} \\times \\text{Ways to arrange 3 digits} = 10 \\times 6 = 60\n\\]\n\nTherefore, the number of 3-digit numbers that can be formed using the digits 2, 3, 4, 7, and 8 without repeating any digits is \\(\\boxed{60}\\).",
